		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    Roleplaying a Dark Elf ShadowKnight</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:badkarma@clanqui.com">Talomyr Valeraine</a> | 
		            11/24/2000 7:58:09 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">Roleplaying a ShadowKnight<BR>
by Talomyr Valeraine<BR>
<BR>
-------------------------------<BR>
Author's note: First and foremost, this roleplaying guide is geared towards the Dark Elven ShadowKnight of Innoruuk.  If you play anything else, find another guide because this is only for the children of Hate.  Also, modifications and personal accomodations are welcome when it comes to roleplaying, this is merely a basis to help set your character in motion.  So, lets continue with the guide.<BR>
<BR>
Developing a Name: First things first, the character has to have a name.  The very first impression you make on anyone here in Everquest is your name.  Names can be attractive, artistic, or downright vulgar.  An attractive name is usually something that holds beauty, the mere mention of the name brings up images of this beauty.  Artistic are the names developed that carry a flow, made up by those with the driving passion to roleplay and write novels about their characters.  Vulgar are the names that are simply there to insult the gaming environment, to dissuade those to remember that Everquest is just a game and not an adventure.  The kind of name you would like is either one that holds beauty or has an artistic flow.  Choose a vulgar name and stop reading this guide, because you will not get any farther in your roleplaying career.<BR>
<BR>
The name Talomyr was derived from 2 things.  Talo came from the god of destruction Talos in AD&amp;D 2nd edition.  While myr came from Cormyr in AD&amp;D 2nd edition.  The Y for an I is usually common for elven names, usually signifies elven decent.  Valeraine was clearly made up from the top of my head.<BR>
<BR>
Background:  Before you start even thinking about how to roleplay your character you must first make a framework on what the character believes and how reactions would occur when encountering certain predicaments.  A background (or history) not only sets a stage for your character, but gives you driving goals to help make the character more tangible.  Ideas for a background are left up to you, for I cannot give ideas because there would be too many similiar backgrounds based on those that read this guide.  All I can say is this, there is always a dramatic scene with an uprising climax.  Get climatic ideas, or scenes to help paint a canvas.<BR>
<BR>
This next bit is Talomyr's rough history of how he came to be.  I wrote it in a span of an hour, so it isn't really fine tuned or any good, to my beliefs anyway.  I will note that if someone takes this background for their own I will be severely peeved.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Born in the City of Neriak in the House Val'Aldumar, Talomyr's family house was considered outcasts within the Dark elven community for their noble deeds and righteous acts.  Many members of the family promoted kindness and caring to help disuade the other racial communities to shed light on their dark tainted skin.  Their actions were noted by all the people that they helped, helping gain precidence with many races of the light.<BR>
<BR>
However, the commotion of this house's actions brought the attention of their father, the prince of hate, Innoruuk.  Furious with what what good these children of hate were doing, he sought to destroy the family and taint the name of Dark Elves to their rightful hated selves.  With a wave of his hand a rush of hate grew amongst the Dark Elven community to flush out all the family in the house Val'Aldumar and destroy them all.  With an orgy of rage the dark elves did as such, slaughtering their own kind to preserve their evil nature and uphold the hate within their kind.  All were slaughtered in the masscre, save one boy... Talomyr.  Kept hidden from the eyes of the enraged, the young boy was able to escape the clutches of Neriak and flee to a nearby town known as Freeport.  Here, he survived on his own, begging for food and nourishment from the passing adventurers, seeking shelter from the hideously bright sunlight, avoiding the guards that glared at him so because of his skin...<BR>
<BR>
Years had passed before he decided to journey back to Neriak, to seek and find those left of his family.  Upon his return he was greeted with open arms, as if nothing had ever happened.  He was confused at first, then sought answers to why his family was massacred.  Alas, his answer led the notion that family never existed.  From the minds of the enraged, the memory of his family were wiped clean.  Their actions and nobility, all forgotten.  Who could of done this?  Talomyr pursued with questions, but answers were left empty with the loss of memory.  Just then, a voice came to him.  &quot;You seek me, is that it child?  You taste the vengeance that you wish to fulfill, but don't know where lies the cup to drink from.  I your father have done this to you, and you alone.  Perhaps now you will understand that nobility and righteous actions have no place here with my children.&quot;  Talomyr was simply paralyzed by the booming voice in his head.  As the voice had subsided, Talomyr screamed with fury and rage.  Hate had grown immensely in his body, the fury burned bright.  Such emotion that he held bottled up had to let out.  He grabbed a passing commoner by the collar and screamed violently as the burning sensation was let out through his hands, charring and incinerating the poor commoner.  With a shallow breath, Talomyr panted over a lifeless pile of bones and he glared to and fro in the empty streets.  Winded from the recent exertion he sought an inn to rest, wondering that had just happened back on the streets.  His thoughts raced wildy in his mind, however sleep came eventually.<BR>
<BR>
At first light, Talomyr awoke to find a strange envelope left beside him at his bedside.  He opened the envelop with a curious glance and found a letter written to him by the guildmaster at the Lodge of the Dead, requesting his presence.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Notice how the story stops where you begin in the game of Everquest.  Standing in the middle of nowhere in a city with a note, a non droppable weapon, a book from the priest of dischord, and food/drink.  Thats where the history stops and you begin.  The background doesn't have to be a complete novel, just a simple summary of key events that help form your character.  Not everything is important, just the climatic events that occur.<BR>
<BR>
Roleplaying: Now comes the joys of playing an evil character in the society of Norrath.  However, this does not mean you get to play a complete and total asshole who can break all the rules of EQ.  KSing and Ninja looting does not constitute being evil, rather, being rude and unfair.  Sure those are evil qualities but you must remember, EQ rules come first.  Otherwise you'll be finding yourself playing a different game real fast.<BR>
<BR>
So first off is to know who you are and what you represent.  Dark Elves are very vain, cocky, and can be snobbish at times.  They hold themselves the highest as the &quot;elite race&quot; above all others.  People are out there to be used til they are no longer useful, and idiots are merely casted aside and sent back to their towns that are deprived of their village idiot.  Ignorance is not tolerated, infact, its frowned upon.<BR>
<BR>
So lets start by looking at reactions with races/classes and views about each.  The following are guidelines that I use for Talomyr.<BR>
<BR>
Races:<BR>
<BR>
Trolls - Adequate fighters and a good meat shield to have around<BR>
Ogres - Merely servants who should only carry things.  Whoever taught them to talk should be hung  <BR>
Iksars - Will never conquer our race even if they seek world domination, though I can tolerate them<BR>
Halflings - Lying backstabbing thieves who are meals in a course rather than adventurers<BR>
Wood elves - I am better than you and always will be, for hate burns in my veins, stay in your forests<BR>
Half elves - Half breeds, no better than the full breed light elves.  I merely laugh at them<BR>
High Elves - Accursed light elves, they shall feel my wrath<BR>
Erudites - Hold promise, more trusting than those humans, also more clever<BR>
Humans - Expendable meat<BR>
Dark Elves - They trust me, though I can't always trust them.  Never know when the rage may hit<BR>
Barbarians - Fine craftsman, but no better then their human brothers<BR>
Dwarves - Dwellers of the underground, our home.  I don't like that<BR>
Gnomes - No better than the halflings or dwarves<BR>
<BR>
Classes:<BR>
<BR>
ShadowKnights - They are better than any other, someone to also rely on<BR>
Paladins - Accursed light hurts my eyes, must find a way to douse it<BR>
Druids - Good nor Evil, they are no threat until the balance is tipped.  When it does, I'll be ready<BR>
Clerics - Healing is a good thing, holy is a bad thing<BR>
Warriors - Meat shield<BR>
Rogues - Stay away from my back and I stay away from your soul<BR>
Monks - Useless<BR>
Necromancers - I aim to please and serve<BR>
Wizards - Wary around these, they don't understand the dead, but do with the elements<BR>
Magicians - If their pet keeps at bay, mine will too<BR>
Enchanters - Beautiful, yet crafty.  Just keep me going and I will keep you alive<BR>
Rangers - Much like their druid counterparts, however have good fighting capability<BR>
<BR>
That basically sums up Talomyr's views towards each race and class.  So if he were to encounter a High Elf Paladin, he wouldn't give any respect, but for a Erudite Necromancer he would.  All on how you piece the race with the class.  <BR>
<BR>
Though you can hold prejudices aside in a group to use them up.  When the group breaks or when you leave the group, you neither know or care who they are.   I have encountered roleplayers who didn't care if a group member dies, just as long as they didn't which is a bit selfish, however it is considered evil.<BR>
<BR>
Channels: Now there are many different channels in which you can type.  Here is a list of the channels and how I respect each as either ic or ooc (In Character or Out Of Character)<BR>
<BR>
/ooc 		-	OOC<BR>
/auction 	- 	OOC<BR>
/shout	-	IC<BR>
/group	-	IC<BR>
/say		-	IC<BR>
/tell		- 	OOC<BR>
/guild		- 	OOC (depending on guild)<BR>
<BR>
Some can be more obvious than, here is my reasoning.  For Auction its nice to use acronyms like WTS, WTT, WTB just to cut down on typing.  That and it requires tells to make transactions, which is also OOC.  Shout is IC of course because you are shouting aloud in the same aspect as saying.  Tells are OOC because sending an immediate tell to someone is not very possible IC when they are on another continent.<BR>
<BR>
Accent: How should your character sound or act?  Should the character speak strictly dark elven?  Should you talk with thous and arts and other old english?  Well that is entirely up to you.  Personally, Talomyr speaks perfect intelligent grammar, with no conjunctions and with a trailing .... to show a quiet tone.  How you speak is totally up to you, however there a few ways you MAY not speak, and that is abbreviated global speech (pls, plz, thxs) or elite speech (w00t, l33t) and other nonesense.  Its just too damn annoying and some of it isn't even real speech.<BR>
<BR>
Reality: In reality, about a mere 5% of players in Everquest ever really roleplay.  So why should you even bother doing it?  Well, in this world we call Norrath (or Everquest, whoever you may be), you will learn quickly that all it really is is going up in levels and finding new places to hunt.  Thats about it.  With roleplaying it spices up your character and makes the days more enjoyable.   It also gives you something to do.<BR>
<BR>
You will also learn that roleplaying is taking sacrifices.  I personally don't like taking buffs from good clerics or even paladins.  I request NOT to have their buffs, just because of its holy nature.  I also don't like to group with paladin's and holy clerics, though sometimes I have to.<BR>
<BR>
Roleplaying can also be a catching virus.  When you start roleplaying, other roleplayers who don't usually roleplay all the time will spark up and catch the roleplay fever.  I have seen it on many occasions, even caught the fever myself.<BR>
<BR>
I also don't roleplaying all the time, there are days where I take breaks to just have fun and meet new people.  I like to get to know people from far away places, its something that I think is fun.<BR>
<BR>
Well that concludes this guide to roleplaying a ShadowKnight.  I hope it was an educational experience and that it helps you formulate your character more into something tangible, rather than something ordinary.<BR>

			<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
					</p>
			</td>
